Reasoning: The paper deals with the problem of finding overlapping communities in complex networks, which is a topic that falls under the broad category of network science. The paper specifically focuses on the computational challenges of the k-clique percolation algorithm, which is a graph-based approach to community detection. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which is dedicated to research on network analysis and modeling. Other likely sub-categories include cs.SD (Software Engineering), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.SY (Systems and Control), and cs.LG (Machine Learning), as these areas are relevant to the computational aspects of the problem.
